# Java Garbage Collection — Interview Notes

## 1. Heap Layout Basics

```
Young Generation                    Old Generation
[ Eden | S0 | S1 ]                  [ ------------------ ]
```

| Space | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **Eden** | Where all new objects are allocated first |
| **S0 / S1 (Survivor)** | Two equal-sized spaces; only one is "active" at any time. Objects that survive a minor GC get copied here |
| **Old Gen (Tenured)** | Objects that survive enough young GC cycles get **promoted** here |

**Why two survivor spaces?** So copying collection always has a clean destination — Eden + active survivor get scanned, live objects copied to the *other* (empty) survivor, then roles swap. This avoids fragmentation in young gen entirely.

**Object lifecycle:**
```
New object → Eden → (survives minor GC) → S0/S1 (age++ each cycle)
           → (age crosses tenuring threshold OR survivor space full) → Old Gen
```

**Interview trap:** "Minor GC" = young gen collection. "Major/Full GC" = old gen (or whole heap) collection. Full GC is always more expensive.

---

## 2. Serial GC (`-XX:+UseSerialGC`) — a.k.a. "Single GC"

- **1 thread** does everything. Full **Stop-The-World (STW)** for both young and old gen.
- **Young gen:** copying collector (Eden/S0/S1 → Cheney-style copy)
- **Old gen:** **Mark → Sweep → Compact** (MSC) — always fully compacts
- Pause time ≈ **O(heap size)** for old gen — bad for large heaps
- **Best for:** small heaps, CLI tools, single-core machines, client-side apps
- **Key fact:** simplest correctness model — world is frozen, no mutator races, no write barriers needed

---

## 3. Parallel GC (`-XX:+UseParallelGC`) — "Throughput collector"

- Same algorithms as Serial (copying young, MSC old) but **multi-threaded** for both
- Still fully STW — just faster because N threads instead of 1
- **Goal: maximize throughput**, not minimize pause time
- Was the **default GC in Java 8**
- **Interview line:** "Parallel = Serial's algorithms, parallelized. Doesn't reduce pause time philosophy, just does the STW work faster."

---

## 4. CMS — Concurrent Mark Sweep (`-XX:+UseConcMarkSweepGC`)

- **Young gen:** handled by **ParNew** (parallel STW copying collector — separate from Parallel Scavenge, built to cooperate with CMS)
- **Old gen:** concurrent mark-sweep — **runs alongside the app**, only 2 short STW pauses

### Phases (memorize this):
| Phase | STW? | What happens |
|---|---|---|
| Initial Mark | STW (short) | Mark objects reachable directly from GC roots |
| Concurrent Mark | Concurrent | Traverse full object graph while app runs |
| Concurrent Preclean | Concurrent | Rescan dirty cards, shrink Remark's workload |
| **Remark** | **STW (bigger)** | Final sync — rescans dirty cards + young gen refs |
| Concurrent Sweep | Concurrent | Reclaim dead objects into **free lists** — **no compaction** |
| Concurrent Reset | Concurrent | Reset bookkeeping for next cycle |

### Core CS concepts to be able to explain:
- **Tricolor marking** (white/gray/black) — invariant: no black object may point to white
- **Write barrier + Card Table**: tracks mutator writes into old gen so collector doesn't rescan everything; card = fixed-size heap chunk (e.g. 512B) marked "dirty" on write
- **Incremental update** algorithm (Dijkstra-style) — CMS's specific write-barrier strategy

### CMS's fatal flaws:
1. **No compaction** → old gen fragments over time (free-list allocation, not bump-pointer)
2. **Promotion failure**: young GC can't promote an object because no single free chunk is big enough in old gen (even if total free space is enough)
3. **Concurrent Mode Failure**: old gen fills up before the concurrent cycle finishes → falls back to full single-threaded compacting STW collection (worst-case pause, worse than Serial would've been)

### Status:
- Deprecated: **Java 9** (JEP 291)
- Removed: **Java 14** (JEP 363) — flag will fail to start JVM

---

## 5. G1 — Garbage First (`-XX:+UseG1GC`)

- **Default since Java 9**; usable from Java 7u4+
- **Fixes CMS's core weakness: fragmentation**, by restructuring heap layout

### Structural change:
- Heap divided into many **equal-sized regions** (1MB–32MB, auto-sized)
- Any region can be Eden, Survivor, or Old — **role assigned dynamically**, no fixed Young/Old blocks

```
G1 heap: [E][E][S][O][E][O][O][E][S][O]...   ← roles reassigned over time
```

### "Garbage First" — the core idea:
- Each region tracks how much garbage it holds
- G1 collects the regions with **best garbage-to-effort ratio first** (not the whole old gen every time)

### Incremental compaction (the big win over CMS):
- G1 **does** compact — but region by region
- Picks a subset of regions → copies live objects OUT to a fresh empty region → **discards the entire source region** (100% reclaimed, not "gaps")
- Never fragments, because it never deletes-in-place — always copies-and-discards, same trick as young-gen copying collection

### Concurrency mechanism — different from CMS:
- **SATB (Snapshot-At-The-Beginning)**, not incremental update
- Logs the **old** value when a reference is overwritten (not the new one) — guarantees anything alive at cycle start stays marked alive
- **Remembered Sets (RSets)** — per-region "who points into me" index, replacing CMS's single global card table. Lets G1 evacuate a few regions without scanning the whole heap for references to them

### Pause time control:
- `-XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=200` — G1 tries to hit this target by choosing how many regions to process
- **Goal-based/predictive**, vs. CMS's threshold-triggered/reactive model

