## 7. Likely Follow-up Interview Questions (with one-liners)

**Q: Why does young gen behave the same under CMS as under Parallel GC?**
A: CMS only replaces old-gen's algorithm. Young gen is handled by ParNew — same copying-collector concept as Parallel Scavenge, just implemented separately to cooperate with CMS's card table/promotion handling.

**Q: Why can't CMS compact concurrently?**
A: Moving a live object while the mutator might hold a raw pointer to its old address isn't safe without stopping the world (or full relocating-collector machinery like ZGC/Shenandoah use). CMS predates that tech, so it just skips compaction.

**Q: What's the tricolor invariant and why does it matter?**
A: No black (fully-scanned, "live") object may point to a white (unvisited) object during concurrent marking — otherwise the collector might sweep up a still-live object as garbage. Write barriers exist specifically to preserve this invariant.

**Q: SATB vs incremental update — what's the actual difference?**
A: Incremental update (CMS) marks newly-created references gray as they're written. SATB (G1) instead logs the *old* value when overwritten, guaranteeing anything alive at snapshot time stays alive for the whole cycle — considered more efficient for concurrent correctness.

**Q: What causes Promotion Failure vs Concurrent Mode Failure?**
A: Promotion Failure = old gen has enough *total* free space but no single chunk big enough (fragmentation). Concurrent Mode Failure = old gen fills up entirely before the CMS cycle finishes reclaiming space. Both trigger fallback to a full STW collection.

**Q: Why did G1 replace CMS?**
A: G1 gives CMS's core benefit (concurrent marking, low pause times) without CMS's core weakness (fragmentation), by compacting incrementally at the region level instead of never compacting at all.

**Q: How do you pick a GC in production today?**
A: G1 is the default/safe choice for most services. Use ZGC/Shenandoah if you need sub-10ms pauses on very large heaps. CMS is legacy-only (removed in Java 14+). Serial/Parallel only for small heaps or pure-throughput batch jobs where pause time doesn't matter.

